sec.p:
Ceratopogonids are one of the most important and diverse groups within the nematocerous 
Diptera
. The family 
Ceratopogonidae
is well known for its medico-veterinary importance (

; 

; 

). Worldwide, there are 6206 extant species placed in three subfamilies belonging to 112 genera (

). The genus 

Forcipomyia
Meigen, 1818

is the second largest speciose group within the family 
Ceratopogonidae
, showing an astonishing diversity with 1142 species worldwide distributed into 36 different subgenera (

). Till date in 
India
, a total of 83 species of 
Forcipomya
are known (

; 

; 

; 

, b).

Like most of the other ceratopogonids, 

Forcipomyia

has also shown a wide range of feeding diversity such as hematophagous, hemolymphophagous, pollinophagous and necterophagous (

). Numerous species belonging to this genus have also been documented as ectoparasites of insects across multiple orders (

; 

).

Our knowledge about the immature stages of the genus 

Forcipomyia

is very poor; only 12 % of the species have their immature stages worldwide (

), and so far one species is known in 
India
(

). The immatures of 

Forcipomyia

are mainly found in semiaquatic and terrestrial habitats like decaying organic matter, rotten wooden parts of plants, phytotelmata, bromeliads, wet moss and algae (

).

Lepidohelea
was erected as a genus by Kieffer based on the type species
Ceratopogon chrysolophus Kieffer, 1911
from Seychelles in 1917. Later,
established
Lepidohelea
as a subgenus of
Forcipomyia .
Forcipomyia ( Lepidohelea ) Kieffer, 1917
has 87 species (83 extant and 4 extinct) around the World (
;
). Till date, five species are known from India (
, b). One of the distinguishing features of this subgenus is that most of the body (especially legs, wings and abdomen) is covered with long flattened scales and there is yellowish brown banding pattern in the legs and body (
). Most of the species within the subgenus occur in dense forest and hilly areas. Members of the subgenus
Lepidohelea
are primarily pollinators, playing a key role in cacao pollination (
;
). The majority of the species have only adult descriptions, among them immature stages of only nine species are described (
). Immature stages are mostly prevalent in terrestrial habitats and are often found in decaying logs, under wood and banana fiber (
;
).

